            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lin Wong was born in the heart of San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, the only child of parents who arrived from Hong Kong in the late 1970s. Her father worked as a chef, her mother as a seamstress, and their lives were shaped by resilience and hard work. Mei grew up in a vibrant, working-class neighborhood, steeped in the aromas of Chinatown and the rhythm of the city\u2019s transit. This early exposure to diverse communities and the constant evolution of her surroundings sparked a fascination with the built environment.\n\nAcademically driven, Mei excelled in school, drawn to subjects that explored communities and infrastructure. She pursued a Bachelor\u2019s Degree in Urban Planning, partially funded by scholarships and her own part-time jobs. Her summer internships with local non-profits ignited a passion for equitable development and sustainable cities.\n\nHer career began with an entry-level position within the San Francisco Planning Department. Over two decades, she steadily climbed the ranks, demonstrating a sharp intellect and an unwavering commitment to public service. A key turning point came during a controversial rezoning project in the Sunset District, where Mei\u2019s meticulous research and calm approach helped bridge divides and find a viable solution. This success solidified her reputation as a capable mediator and strategic thinker. She now holds the position of Senior City Planner, a role that allows her to shape key policy decisions regarding housing, transportation, and urban development.\n\nMei remains close to her parents, who now live in a smaller apartment in the Outer Richmond. While she never married, she maintains a close-knit circle of friends from university and work. Her weekends are often spent exploring new parks, volunteering at a Chinatown youth center, or hosting potlucks with her friends.\n\nHer current lifestyle is comfortable but not extravagant. She resides in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset, a location that allows her to easily commute via Muni to her downtown office. Her income affords her a comfortable existence, allowing for occasional travel and supporting her parents.\n\nMei\u2019s deepest connection is to San Francisco itself. She sees the city\u2019s complexities and challenges but also its immense potential for progress and inclusivity. Her hopes lie in shaping a future where San Francisco\u2019s growth benefits all its residents, ensuring affordable housing, accessible transit, and vibrant, sustainable neighborhoods. Her aspirations are not for personal wealth or fame, but for leaving a lasting positive impact on the city that raised her."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  The scent of fresh bread and salty air filled her senses as Mei, maybe five years old, clutched her father\u2019s hand on a chilly evening walk through Golden Gate Park. He pointed out the Conservatory of Flowers, glowing softly. It was a quiet moment of pure connection, a feeling of being safe and loved in a city that felt vast and full of wonders yet to be discovered. It instilled in her a deep love for the beauty tucked into the urban landscape.\n\n2.  Sitting cross-legged on the worn linoleum of their Richmond apartment kitchen, Mei watched her mother meticulously stitch a vibrant silk dress. Her mother\u2019s hands moved with practiced grace, transforming fabric into something beautiful. It was a silent lesson in patience and craftsmanship, a realization that dedication and hard work could create something substantial and lasting, a principle that would later define her approach to urban planning. This memory is particularly poignant for Mei; she was around ten years old when this occurred.\n\n3.  The rumble of the 38 Geary bus was the soundtrack to her adolescence. One afternoon, crammed amongst diverse faces and languages, Mei watched the city unfold \u2013 the ornate Victorians of the Richmond transition into the bustle of Downtown. It wasn't a specific event, but the daily immersion in this moving microcosm of San Francisco cemented her understanding of connectivity and the vital role of public transit in knitting communities together, a passion she\u2019d pursue throughout her career. This was her daily bus route for most of her teenage years.\n\n4.  Standing on a podium, nerves fluttering, Mei presented her college thesis on affordable housing policy, her voice shaking initially. Looking out at the faces of her professors and peers, she felt a surge of purpose. It was the moment her academic pursuits transformed into a genuine desire to make a difference, confirming her path into urban planning and solidifying her conviction that equitable development was essential. This was during her final year of university.\n\n5.  The tension in the room was palpable during the Sunset rezoning meeting. Mei, then a mid-level planner, explained complex data simply, listened patiently to heated arguments, and proposed a compromise. When a resident, initially skeptical, eventually nodded in understanding, a quiet wave of relief and satisfaction washed over her. This experience, occurring in her late thirties, solidified her belief in the power of dialogue and collaboration to navigate the city\u2019s inherent complexities."
